WEBVTT

00:24.280 --> 00:28.860
CHAPTER V. TENNESS AND THE IMMORTAL SOUL

00:30.880 --> 00:58.840
You get into the morning train with your newspaper, and you calmly and majestically give yourself up to your newspaper. You do not hurry. You know you have at least half an hour of security in front of you. As your glance lingers idly at the advertisements of shipping and of songs on the outer pages, your air is the air of a leisured man, wealthy in time, of a man from some planet where there are

00:58.840 --> 01:26.560
a hundred and twenty-four hours a day, instead of twenty-four. I am an impassioned reader of newspapers. I read five English and two French dailies, and the newsagents alone know how many weeklies, regularly. I am obliged to mention this personal fact, lest I should be accused of a prejudice against newspapers, when I say that I object to the reading of newspapers in the morning train.

01:27.640 --> 01:56.540
Newspapers are produced with rapidity, to be read with rapidity. There is no place in my daily program for newspapers. I read them, as I may, in odd moments, but I do read them, the idea of devoting to them thirty or forty consecutive minutes of wonderful solitude, for nowhere can one more perfectly immerse oneself in oneself than in a compartment full of silent, withdrawn, smothered, and empty.

01:56.560 --> 02:23.700
I cannot possibly allow you to scatter priceless pearls of time with such oriental lavishness. You are not the shah of time. Let me respectfully remind you that you have no more time than I have, no newspaper reading in trains. I have already put by about three-quarters of an hour for use.

02:24.900 --> 02:29.600
Now you reach your office, and I abandon you there till six o'clock.

02:30.160 --> 02:36.460
I am aware that you have nominally an hour, often in reality an hour and a half, in the

02:36.460 --> 02:40.280
midst of the day, less than half of which time is given to eating.

02:41.000 --> 02:44.200
But I will leave you all that to spend as you choose.

02:44.440 --> 02:46.420
You may read your newspapers then.

02:47.460 --> 02:50.580
I meet you again as you emerge from your office.

02:50.920 --> 02:52.640
You are pale and tired.

02:53.160 --> 02:58.540
At any rate, your wife says you are pale and you give her to understand that you are tired.

02:59.740 --> 03:04.860
During the journey home, you have been gradually working up the tired feeling.

03:05.600 --> 03:11.780
The tired feeling hangs heavy over the mighty suburbs of London like a virtuous and melancholy

03:11.780 --> 03:14.240
cloud, particularly in winter.

03:14.960 --> 03:20.760
You don't eat immediately on your arrival home, but in about an hour or so you feel

03:20.760 --> 03:24.220
as if you could sit up and take a little nourishment.

03:24.640 --> 03:25.640
And you do.

03:26.240 --> 03:28.200
Then you smoke seriously.

03:28.800 --> 03:29.760
You see friends.

03:30.280 --> 03:31.100
You potter.

03:31.520 --> 03:32.640
You play cards.

03:32.960 --> 03:34.120
You flirt with a book.

03:34.780 --> 03:37.240
You note that old age is creeping on.

03:37.720 --> 03:38.980
You take a stroll.

03:39.320 --> 03:40.800
You caress the piano.

03:41.320 --> 03:43.920
By Jove, a quarter past eleven.

03:44.740 --> 03:48.720
You then devote quite forty minutes to thinking about going to bed.

03:48.960 --> 03:53.100
And it is conceivable that you are acquainted with a genuinely good whiskey.

03:54.160 --> 03:57.900
At last you go to bed, exhausted by the day's work.

03:58.400 --> 04:02.980
Six hours, probably more, have gone since you left the office.

04:03.300 --> 04:04.620
Gone like a dream.

04:05.160 --> 04:06.540
Gone like magic.

04:07.340 --> 04:08.700
Unaccountably gone.

04:10.500 --> 04:12.600
That is a fair sample case.

04:12.980 --> 04:17.100
But you say it's all very well for you to talk.

04:17.100 --> 04:19.180
A man is tired.

04:19.520 --> 04:21.360
A man must see his friends.

04:21.760 --> 04:23.920
He can't always be on the stretch.

04:24.940 --> 04:25.980
Just so.

04:26.360 --> 04:32.120
But when you arrange to go to the theatre, especially with a pretty woman, what happens?

04:32.580 --> 04:34.080
You rush to the suburbs.

04:34.480 --> 04:38.160
You spare no toil to make yourself glorious and fine raiment.

04:38.780 --> 04:40.980
You rush back to town in another train.

04:41.500 --> 04:45.500
You keep yourself on the stretch for four hours, if not five.

04:45.920 --> 04:47.260
You take her home.

04:47.660 --> 04:48.980
You take yourself home.

04:49.480 --> 04:53.340
You don't spend three-quarters of an hour in thinking about going to bed.

04:53.840 --> 04:54.660
You go.

04:55.300 --> 04:58.140
Friends and fatigue have equally been forgotten.

04:58.520 --> 05:01.780
And the evening has seemed so exquisitely long.

05:02.220 --> 05:03.920
Or perhaps too short.

05:04.980 --> 05:09.740
And do you remember that time when you were persuaded to sing in the chorus of the Amateur

05:09.740 --> 05:15.080
Operatic Society and slaved two hours every other night for three months?

05:15.940 --> 05:20.780
Can you deny that when you have something definite to look forward to at even tide,

05:21.260 --> 05:26.780
something that is to employ all your energy, the thought of that something gives a glow

05:26.780 --> 05:30.280
and a more intense vitality to the whole day?

05:31.700 --> 05:38.200
What I suggest is that at six o'clock you look facts in the face and admit that you are not

05:38.200 --> 05:44.160
tired, because you are not, you know, and that you arrange your evening so that it is

05:44.160 --> 05:46.160
not cut in the middle by a meal.

05:46.840 --> 05:51.340
By so doing you will have a clear expanse of at least three hours.

05:51.860 --> 05:57.100
I do not suggest that you should employ three hours every night of your life in using up

05:57.100 --> 05:58.240
your mental energy.

05:58.920 --> 06:06.040
But I do suggest that you might, for commencement, employ an hour and a half every other evening

06:06.040 --> 06:09.800
in some important and consecutive cultivation of the mind.

06:10.720 --> 06:16.320
You will still be left with three evenings for friends, bridge, tennis, domestic scenes,

06:16.840 --> 06:22.280
odd reading, pipes, gardening, pottering, and prize competitions.

06:22.800 --> 06:29.140
You will still have the terrific wealth of 45 hours between 2 p.m. Saturday and 10 a.m.

06:29.140 --> 06:29.680
Monday.

06:30.620 --> 06:37.820
If you persevere, you will soon want to pass four evenings, and perhaps five, in some sustained

06:37.820 --> 06:43.700
endeavor to be genuinely alive, and you will fall out of that habit of muttering to yourself

06:43.700 --> 06:45.560
at 11.15 p.m.

06:46.060 --> 06:48.680
Time to be thinking about going to bed.

06:49.680 --> 06:55.460
The man who begins to go to bed 40 minutes before he opens his bedroom door is bored.

06:56.000 --> 06:58.700
That is to say, he is not living.

07:00.080 --> 07:07.440
But remember, at the start, those 90 nocturnal minutes, thrice a week, must be the most important

07:07.440 --> 07:09.580
minutes in the 10,080.

07:10.260 --> 07:15.680
They must be sacred, quite as sacred as a dramatic rehearsal or a tennis match.

07:16.440 --> 07:22.220
Instead of saying, sorry, I can't see you, old chap, but I have to run off to the tennis

07:22.220 --> 07:22.600
club.

07:23.060 --> 07:26.240
You must say, but I have to work.

07:27.100 --> 07:30.100
This I admit is intensely difficult to say.

07:30.680 --> 07:34.360
Tennis is so much more urgent than the immortal soul.

